@node Introduction, Invoking, Copying, Top
@chapter Introduction

GNU Typist is an interactive typing tutor  program. It uses an input file to
create a series of typing  tutorials, drills, and timed speed tests.  It
is intended to be used in a raw terminals without graphics ---it has been
compiled and used in GNU and  Unix (GNU/Linux, Aix, Solaris) and also in
DOS/Windows (DOS 6.22, Windows 98, Windows NT).

The program read lessons written  in a very easy scripting language.  It
is distributed with several complete and good lessons, you can use them,
modify them or create new lessons (@pxref{Script files and commands}).

There are two  types of drill - one-time, and  ordinary.  In an ordinary
drill, gtypist  displays text on  the screen, and  waits for the  user to
correctly  type the exact  same text,  underneath.  It  indicates typing
errors, and  if at the  end of the  exercise there were errors,  it will
re-run the drill, up to a maximum number of tries.  In a one-time drill,
the action  is the  same, except  that the program  will not  repeat the
drill  if  it is  not  typed correctly.  Backspace  and  delete are  not
permitted in drills.

In a speed  test, gtypist displays text on the screen,  and waits for the
user to  correctly over-type the  exact same text.  It  indicates typing
errors, and at the end of  the test it calculates the real and effective
rate in WPM.  A  speed test is run only once, no  matter how many errors
there  were.   Backspace and  delete  are  permitted,  but errors  still
accumulate.

The top  line of the screen displays  a banner.  The bottom  line of the
screen displays  a message line, queries, and  other status information.
The  lines in  between are  used for  the tutorials,  drills,  and speed
tests.

If  a script file is not  specified on  the command  line, a  default file
@file{gtypist.typ} will  be used.  (See details about the path in the section 
 @pxref{Environment Variables}). 

In typing  speed reports, a 'word'  is deemed to be  five characters, so
the raw  (gross) WPM is  the number of  characters in the  test passage,
divided by five, then divided again by the number of minutes elapsed in
typing the passage.  The adjusted  WPM factors in the errors; each error
is counted as a word mistyped.

@node Invoking, Script files and commands, Introduction, Top
@chapter Invoking

The syntax to invoke GNU Typist is:

@code{gtypist [ Options... ] [ script_file ]}

The  supported options  are  given below  (note  that the  long form  is
supported only in GNU/Linux):

@table @code
@item -d,--drill_tries
Specifies  the maximum number  of drill  tries permitted.   When running
through an ordinary typing drill, gtypist will not proceed past the drill
until  it is  completed without  errors, or  until the  number  of tries
exceeds drill_tries.   The default  value is 3,  the minimum 1,  and the
maximum 1000.  This value is ignored for one-time typing drills.

@item -n, --notimer
gtypist will display the typing speeds in WPM after both drills and speed
tests.  However,  the lessons  appear to be  written for a  program that
only does this for speed tests.   To make gtypist behave in a manner that
matches the lessons,  that is, to sup WPM  reports on drills, use
-n, --notimer.

@item -t, --term_cursor
gtypist  creates its own  flashing block  cursor on  the screen,  to help
distinguish  between the  cursor  and reverse  video error  indications.
Setting -t or --term_cursor suppresses this, and forces the program to
use the terminal's cursor instead.

@item -f, --curs_flash
The curs_flash value  sets the block cursor flash period  in tenths of a
second.  A  value of 0 indi cates no cursor flashing.   The default is
10,  and  the  maximum  is  512.   This  option  is  ignored  if  -t  or
--term_cursor has been set.

@item -c, --colo[u]rs
In  normal  operation,  gtypist   uses  only  normal  and  reverse  video
attributes in monochrome  mode.  This option may be  used to specify the
foreground  and background  colours on  terminals that  support colours.
The  colours are  specified as  two integers, in  the range  0  to 7,
separated by commas, setting the foreground and background colours.  The
colour codes 0  to 7 indicate black, red,  green, yellow, blue, magenta,
cyan, and  white respec tively.  The default  colours string is  7,0 -
white on black.  The option is  ignored if the terminal does not support
colours.

@item -s, --silent 
When gtypist detects a typing error, it will beep the terminal.  Use this
option to silence the beep.

@item -q, --quiet
Same as -s, --silent.

@item -w, --wpmode
By default, gtypist will try to  mimic a word processor in certain ways
when executing an exercise.  It will treat space at the end of a line as
a correctly  typed character, and word wrap.  It  will treat return at
the end of a line as a signal to move to the start of the next paragraph
if  applicable.   It will  compress multiple  spaces into  a  single
space.  And it will skip over hyphens  found at the end of a line.  This
option will turn off these word processor-like actions.

@item -l, --start_label
Specifies the label in the  script_file at which gtypist begins executing
(see script  files and  commands below for  information on  labels).  If
start_label is not  given, gtypist begins execution at  the first line of
the file.

@end table

