@node Script files and commands, Supplied lessons, Invoking, Top
@chapter Script files and commands

GNU Typist reads  in the data for  its typing lessons from a script file.
With the exception of comments and blank lines, each line in the file is
of the format

@code{command_char : command_data}

@noindent
Here,  @code{command_char} is a  single character  code that  defines an
action for  gtypist to  take, and @code{command_data}  is data  for that
command.  If @code{command_char} is a  space character, this indicates that the
line  is a  continuation of  the preceding  non-space command.   The ':'
separator must be in column two of the line.


Comment  lines  are lines  beginning  with  a  '!'  character,  and  are
ignored, as are blank lines.  Comment lines may have any format provided
that they begin with '!'; other lines must have the above format.

The following is a list of valid @code{command_char} values:

@table @code
@item B
This  command  clears  the  complete  screen.  If  any  @code{command_data}  is
present, this  is displayed  in the  one-line banner at  the top  of the
screen, and remains in place until the next @code{B} command.  This command may
not be continued; it is a single line command.

@item *
This indicates a label in the file.  The label may be the target of a @code{G},
@code{Y}, or @code{N} command.  Labels may contain any character, including space, and are a single line command.

@item T
This  presents a  tutorial,  and is  a  multi line  command,  up to  the
available size of the curses screen.  Each line in the command is simply
printed to the  screen.  This command clears the  screen beneath the top
banner line.

@item l
This presents  some instructions  to prefix a  drill or speed  test.  At
most  two lines are  permitted.  It  clears the  screen beneath  the top
banner line.

@item D
This creates an  ordinary typing drill.  It is  a multi-line command; as
many lines may be used as are available to curses.

@item O
This creates  a one-time typing drill.   It is a  multi-line command; as
many lines may be used as are available to curses.

@item P
This creates a speed test.  It  is a multi-line command; as many lines
may be used as are available to curses.

@item G
This causes  gtypist to  go to  the label in  command_data,  and resume
execution of the script there.  This is a single line command.

@item Q
This uses  the message line at the  bottom of the display  to prompt the
user for  a Yes/No response.  command_data  is used as  the query.  Only
the @key{Y} and @key{N} keys may be used to respond.

@item Y
This is like @code{G},  except that the goto is executed only  if the result of
the last @code{Q} command was @key{Y}.

@item N
This is like @code{G},  except that the goto is executed only  if the result of
the last @code{Q} command was @key{N}.

@item K
This  binds a function  key to  a label.   The format  of the  data line
following this command must be @code{fkey_number:label}, where 
@code{fkey_number} is
a function key number in the range 1 to 12, and @code{label} is a label to go
to when  this key  is pressed.  A  value of  NULL for label  removes any
label binding from  the key. 

If function  keys are not  available on the  terminal other keys  can be
used: @key{1} to @key{9} to replace @key{F1} to @key{F9},  @key{0} to 
replace @key{F10}, @key{A} for @key{F11} and @key{S} for @key{F12}.

Other  alternatives  for  the  keys  @key{F1}  to  @key{F12}  are  the
combinations: @key{Ctrl-Q},  @key{Ctrl-W}, @key{Ctrl-E}, @key{Ctrl-R}, 
@key{Ctrl-T}, @key{Ctrl-Z}, @key{Ctrl-U}, @key{Ctrl-I}, 
@key{Ctrl-O}, @key{Ctrl-P}, @key{Ctrl-A} and @key{Ctrl-S}.

This is also useful  where function keys are inter­ cepted
by other programs, for example, a window manager.

@item X
This command causes  gtypist to exit.  It is a  single line command.  Any
command data is ignored.

@end table


Here is a tiny example script to demonstrate the available commands:

@example
